		<!------------------------ Main Content Section ---------------------------------->
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<a href="./workshop_list.asp">Click here</a> to view the complete list of workshops.
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				Select a track to view full session information:
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 1:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=1">The New Rules of Business: Responding to growth and change.</a></strong>
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 2:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=2">Development: Opportunities and challenges ahead.</a></strong>
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 3:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=3">Online, Mobile, Handheld Games: Taking Measure of Their Gaming Growth.</a></strong>			
			</p>	


			
			
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 1</strong>
				<br><strong>The New Rules of Business</strong>
				<br>The game industry's transition from niche market to a leading member of the entertainment community is now complete. Computer, console, and hand-held games compete vigorously with movies, music, and TV. And when the game industry isn't competing with other entertainment sectors, it is collaborating with them in the areas of simultaneous content development, cross-marketing, and cross-promotion initiatives. This year's business track will look at what this rise in collaboration means for the game industry, as well as topics as diverse as how contracts between developers and publishers are written today and how new trends in marketing and cross-promotion are creating new opportunities for the industry.<br><br>As the game industry broadens its reach and looks toward a new generation of superior consoles, more advanced PC and online games, and a more crowded handheld space, knowing how to compete intelligently has never been more important.  
			</p>			

		
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.1 - No session during this time slot</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">TBD&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.2 - Partnering With The Movie, Music And TV Industries: Profit from the New Level of Collaboration</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Getting “into the game” has never been viewed as more desirable then it is now by movie studios, its top-tier talent, bands, TV production companies, and music execs. From jointly-created brands and intellectual properties, to sharing assets (including talent), to using games to launch new products, never have the industries worked so closely to leverage each other’s strengths. This session will look at recent successes that came of this collaboration and inform attendees how the   game industry can take advantage of its new standing among these related entertainment fields.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Joshua Grode, Partner - Liner Yankelevitz Sunshine & Regenstreif LLP&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Steve Allison, Chief Marketing Officer - Midway Games<br>Don Daglow, President and Chief Executive Officer - Stormfront Studios<br>Jason Hall, Senior Vice President - Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment<br>Charles Hirschhorn, Founder and Chief Executive Officer - G4<br>Larry Shapiro, Creative Artists Agency&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.3 - Marketing Games In The New Age Of Entertainment (Part I):  Detecting the Gen Y Consumer</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">The game industry represents not only today's most dynamic area of entertainment, but also the future of how consumers--growing up in a digitally interactive world--expect to be entertained. If you want to own any significant market share in the future games marketplace, regardless of platform, or target audience, you need to start listening to and understanding this next wave of consumers. How do they like to spend their time? How much are they willing to spend on entertainment? What are they looking for from virtual worlds? How do they view brands? What are their tolerance levels for brand intrusion? This session will identify today’s and tomorrow’s Alpha Consumer and introduce attendees to the motivations, ambitions, preferences, and expectations of this key demographic group.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Richard Ow, Senior Industry Analyst - NPD Funworld Video Games&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Jane Buckingham, President - Youth Intelligence<br>Sean Denny, Senior Manager of Strategic Marketing - LucasArts Entertainment<br>Eric Johnson, Chief Executive Officer - Ignited Minds&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.4 - Marketing Games In The New Age of Entertainment (Part II): Reaching and Selling the Gen Y Consumer</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 3:30 PM - 4:30 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">To effectively communicate with the key audience of 18-35 year-old consumers, game marketers are infusing a combination of standard marketing and promotion techniques with radical ideas that are revolutionizing the way traditional advertisers look at and connect with consumers.  This session will explore new trends and the future direction of game marketing, and what the coming convergence with other mediums and industries--who, in an effort to be a part of this new market are seeking cross-promotional tie-ins, partnerships, and even a convergence with interactive game content--means for today's game marketers and developers. Attendees will gain a greater understanding of the most effective new trends in game marketing and the expanding possibilities for partnerships with other industries, outside the games turf.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Craig Relyea, Executive Vice President, Marketing - Creative Domain&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Beth Featherstone, Senior Director of Product Marketing - Microsoft Game Dvision<br>Jeff Karp, Vice President of Marketing - Electronic Arts<br>Tony Kee, Vice President of Marketing - Ubisoft&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.5 - Toward an Artisan Model of Game Design</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">In an era of big-budget games scaled to selling millions of units, is there a place for games driven by intuition, originality, and artistic vision? How is it possible to create successful games using an artisan approach? Hear from developers who have gone with their gut and have successfully combined commercial success with artistic integrity.  Hear how a development process based on intuition is valid in today’s highly competitive, high risk game world, and how an artesian model can yield a top-selling game.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Richard Rouse, III, Lead Designer - Surreal Software&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Lorne Lanning, President and Creative Director - Oddworld Inhabitants<br>Brian Reynolds, President - Big Huge Games<br>Chris Taylor, President and Designer - Gas Powered Games<br>Feargus Urquhart, Chief Executive Officer - Obsidian Entertainment&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.6 - Tapping New Revenue Streams from Traditional Game Assets</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">As the cost of developing and promoting games rises, many developers and publishers are finding new ways to generate revenue from game assets. From game engines that are being used by movie and TV animators, to opportunities for product placement in games, to collaborating with tournament sites and securing contracts with the U.S. government, developers and publishers are devising new ways to drive additional income their way. Learn how game assets present not only a playground for gamers, but also an opportunity to amortize the high cost of development. Be smart about maximizing a return on your investment by hearing firsthand where new opportunities exist.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Amy Bernstein, Senior Editor - Business 2.0&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Tim Ansell, President, CEO, Founder and Owner - The Creative Assembly, Ltd<br>Todd Hollenshead, Chief Executive Officer and Co-Owner - id Software<br>David Lawee, Chief Operating Officer/Chief Financial Officer - Ultimate Arena<br>Josh Resnick, President - Pandemic Studios&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.7 - Business Summit: Follow the Leaders</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">As the game industry continues to grow, knowing where the market is headed is essential in participating in the industry’s growth. This session will assemble key personnel from the game industry’s most successful publishing companies as well as the top online entertainment and media site and ask them to discuss how they are preparing their companies to capitalize on the growing appetite for interactive entertainment. Take a front row seat as a quartet of industry visionaries and decision-makers tell us where they believe this entertainment sector is headed, how they are leveraging their current product and service lineup for future growth, and what areas are ripe for development.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Scott McGrew, News Technology/Business Reporter - KNTV, San Jose&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Jay Cohen, Vice President Publishing - Ubisoft<br>Gerhard Florin, Senior Vice President and Managing Director, European Publishing - Electronic Arts<br>Jim Moloshok, Senior Vice President, Media and Entertainment - Yahoo!<br>Russell Shanks, Chief Operating Officer - Sony Online Entertainment&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>1.8 - On the Front Lines of Tomorrow’s Games: Trends in the Hiring Trenches</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 3:30 PM - 4:30 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 404AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">As games gravitate online, integrate the use of new peripherals, and are programmed for a wider array of mobile platforms, the skill sets required to build and market those games will look nothing like today’s. What skills will be required to build the next generation of games? What skills will game companies be looking for from its marketing, PR, and finance specialists? How can you best prepare yourself to advance your career within the same company (yes, it can happen). Get an inside view of how the industry’s biggest employers are planning on maximizing efficiencies within their own organizations, who they’ll be looking to hire, how they plan on training current employees to assume new responsibilities, and what skills they will be looking for to support the increased number of multiplayer and persistent world games on their production and development schedules. Find out what the most desirable skill sets are from those companies who are building their future hiring strategies today.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
